    list1.append(movies[movies.Genre == gen].BudgetMillions) #creates list of lists
    mylabels.append(gen) # for legend
plt.hist(list1, bins = 30, stacked = True,rwidth = 1, label = mylabels)
plt.legend()
plt.show()

Boxplots vs Violinplots

In [53]:

# insights: action has bulk ratings b/n 30 - 40. thrillers have bulk b/n 60 - 85
In [54]:
z1 = sns.violinplot(data = movies, x = movies.Genre, y = movies.CriticRating)
# similar to boxplots, just more visual where bulk data is concentrated

In [101]:
g = sns.FacetGrid(movies, row = 'Genre', col = 'Year', hue = 'Genre')
kws = dict(s = 50, linewidth = 0.5, edgecolor = 'black')  # enable adjustments to output
g = g.map(plt.scatter, 'CriticRating', 'AudienceRating', **kws )
# Controlling Axis and Adding Diagonals
g.set(xlim = (10, 100), ylim = (0, 100))  # set range for x and y axis
for ax in g.axes.flat:   # allows u to iterate over array of plots
    ax.plot((0, 100), (0,100), c = 'gray', ls = '--')
g.add_legend() # add legend to chart

Building Dashboards

In [129]:
f, axes = plt.subplots(3, 2, figsize = (15, 15))
sns.set_style('darkgrid')
k1 = sns.kdeplot(movies.BudgetMillions, movies.AudienceRating, ax = axes[0, 0])
k2 = sns.kdeplot(movies.BudgetMillions, movies.CriticRating, ax = axes[0, 1])
k1.set(xlim = (-20, 160)) # set range for x - axis
k2.set(xlim = (-20, 160))
axes[2,0].hist(movies.BudgetMillions, label = 'Budget in Millions') # NB: For plt plots without ax parameter, use this approach
z1 = sns.violinplot(data = movies, x = movies.Genre, y = movies.CriticRating, ax = axes[1,0])
m1 = sns.kdeplot(movies.CriticRating, movies.AudienceRating, shade = True, cmap = 'Reds', shade_lowest = False, ax = axes[1,1] )
m2 = sns.kdeplot(movies.CriticRating, movies.AudienceRating, cmap = 'Reds', ax = axes[1,1] )
plt.show()

In [199]:
f, axes = plt.subplots(3, 2, figsize = (15, 15))
sns.set_style('dark', {'axes.facecolor': 'white'}) # used dic in set_style for axes background
# Plot 0,0
k1 = sns.kdeplot(movies.BudgetMillions, movies.AudienceRating, ax = axes[0, 0], 
                 shade = True, shade_lowest = True, cmap = 'inferno') # NB: cmp error provides list of colours to use
k1b = sns.kdeplot(movies.BudgetMillions, movies.AudienceRating, ax = axes[0, 0], cmap = 'cool')
# Plot 0,1
k2 = sns.kdeplot(movies.BudgetMillions, movies.CriticRating, ax = axes[0, 1],
                 shade = True, shade_lowest = True, cmap = 'inferno')
k2 = sns.kdeplot(movies.BudgetMillions, movies.CriticRating, ax = axes[0, 1], cmap = 'cool')

k1.set(xlim = (-20, 160)) # set range for x - axis
k2.set(xlim = (-20, 160))
# Plot 2,0
axes[2,0].hist(movies.BudgetMillions, label = 'Budget in Millions') # NB: For plt plots without ax parameter, use this approach
# Plot 1,0
z1 = sns.violinplot(data = movies, x = movies.Genre, y = movies.CriticRating, palette = 'YlOrRd', ax = axes[1,0])
# Plot 1,1
m1 = sns.kdeplot(movies.CriticRating, movies.AudienceRating, shade = True, cmap = 'Blues', shade_lowest = False, ax = axes[1,1] )
m2 = sns.kdeplot(movies.CriticRating, movies.AudienceRating, cmap = 'gist_gray_r', ax = axes[1,1] )
plt.show()

Thematic Edits

In [263]:
# Loop to implement stacked histograms for all Genre categories
list1 = [] # creates empty list
mylabels = []
for gen in movies.Genre.cat.categories:
    list1.append(movies[movies.Genre == gen].BudgetMillions) # creates list of lists
    mylabels.append(gen) # for legend

fig1, ax = plt.subplots() # done to adjust overall size of figure
fig1.set_size_inches(11.7, 8.27) # size of A4 paper

plt.hist(list1, bins = 30, stacked = True,rwidth = 1, label = mylabels)
h = plt.legend(title = 'Legend', frameon = True, shadow = True, fontsize = 'medium', prop = {'size': 15} ) # adjust legend
h.get_title().set_fontsize(16) # adjust legend title font size
sns.set_style('whitegrid') # adjusts chart background

plt.xlabel('Budget in Millions',fontsize = 15, fontstyle = 'italic', color = 'Magenta') # add x - axis label
plt.ylabel('Number of Movies',fontsize = 15, fontstyle = 'normal', color = 'DarkGray')

plt.xticks(fontsize = 12, fontstyle = 'oblique') # adjust x- axis ticks
plt.yticks(fontsize = 15, fontstyle = 'oblique')
plt.title('Movie Budget Distribution', fontsize = 20, fontname =  'console', color = 'Blue') # add title
plt.show()
